{
  "local_port": 41126,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights at an airport, also known as making a connecting flight, can seem overwhelming, but with some preparation, it can be relatively straightforward. Here\u2019s how you can manage your connection in Paris:\n\n1. **Know Your Itinerary:** Ensure you have all the details about your flights, including the terminal, gate numbers, and boarding times for each flight. These details are typically available on your e-ticket or can be checked online.\n\n2. **Arrival in Paris:**\n   - Upon arrival at Paris Charles de Gaulle Airport (CDG), follow the signs for connecting flights.\n   - If you arrive at Orly (ORY) instead, the process should be similar, but note that these are separate airports, so the procedures may slightly vary.\n\n3. **Customs and Immigration:**\n   - If you're arriving from outside the Schengen Area and your final destination is within the Schengen Area (like Prague), you'll likely go through passport control in Paris.\n   - Make sure your passport and any necessary visas are in order for entry into the Schengen Area.\n\n4. **Terminal and Gate Information:**\n   - Check the airline or airport monitors for the most up-to-date departure hall, gate numbers, and possible changes.\n   - CDG is a large airport with multiple terminals. Some connections may require a shuttle or train ride between terminals.\n\n5. **Security Checks:**\n   - Be prepared to go through security screening again. Ensure you comply with the regulations concerning liquids, electronics, and other items.\n\n6. **Luggage:**\n   - Verify whether your luggage will be checked through to Prague or if you need to collect it in Paris and check it in again. This is often the case with flights on separate tickets or different airlines that do not have interline agreements.\n   - If your luggage is checked through, you can focus on getting yourself to the next gate.\n\n7. **Connection Time:**\n   - Ensure you have enough time between flights. International airports usually recommend a minimum of two hours for international connections, but more time may be necessary during busy travel periods or if transferring between terminals.\n\n8. **Seek Assistance if Needed:**\n   - If you are unsure where to go, airport staff or information desks are usually helpful. Don\u2019t hesitate to ask for directions or assistance.\n\n9. **Stay Informed:**\n   - Monitor your flight status using airline apps or airport displays to be aware of any changes or delays.\n\n10. **Relax:**\n    - Once through security and at your gate, relax and take note of the time your boarding will start.\n\nWith good time management and by following these steps, your connection in Paris should go smoothly. Safe travels!",
